## 2. Simulation-to-Production Mapping

### Design Rationale
This simulation is a deliberately **miniaturized subset** of the full AURORA production network
(Segment 1 design). Two key deviations are intentional and documented here for the grader:

1. **IP Addressing:** The production design uses `10.10.x.x` (Freiburg HQ). The simulation uses
   `172.16.x.x` to avoid address conflicts with UTM's NAT range (`192.168.64.0/24`) and to
   clearly separate lab traffic from hypervisor management traffic.

2. **SIEM Platform:** The production design specifies Splunk / Microsoft Sentinel (enterprise
   licenses). The simulation uses **Wazuh 4.14.3** as the open-source equivalent, providing
   identical functionality (log collection, indexing, alerting, dashboards) within lab resource
   constraints.

### VLAN Mapping: Simulation → Production

| Simulation VLAN | Simulation Name | Production VLAN (Segment 1) | Production Name | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **30** | IT & Infrastructure | **30** | IT & Infrastructure | SIEM and IT systems live here in both designs |
| **40** | Consulting | **40** | Consulting | Client workstations (Win11 represents a consulting endpoint) |
| n/a | External attacker | **n/a** | n/a | Kali sits on WAN (192.168.64.x) — simulates external internet attacker, NOT internal VLAN 51. VLAN 51 (Dirty Lab Sandbox) is an internal isolated zone not simulated in this minimal lab. |

