## 5. Security Rules & Traffic Flow

### Firewall Rules on pfSense (Inter-VLAN)

Rules are applied per interface in pfSense (em1 = VLAN30 rules, em2 = VLAN40 rules).
Traffic between VLANs must route through pfSense — firewall enforces zone policy.

#### VLAN 40 (Consulting/em2) → VLAN 30 (IT & Infra/em1)
```
✅ ALLOW: Win11 (172.16.40.100) → Wazuh (172.16.30.10) TCP 1514, 1515  [Wazuh agent]
✅ ALLOW: Switch-1 (172.16.40.11) → Wazuh (172.16.30.10) TCP 1514, 1515 [Wazuh agent]
❌ DENY:  All other VLAN40 → VLAN30 traffic
```

#### VLAN 30 (IT & Infra/em1) → VLAN 40 (Consulting/em2)
```
✅ ALLOW: Wazuh (172.16.30.10) → any  [agent management outbound]
❌ DENY:  All other VLAN30 → VLAN40 traffic
```

#### WAN (Kali/em0) → Internal VLANs
```
❌ DENY:  All inbound by default (pfSense WAN default behaviour)
✅ ALLOW: Manual rules added during attack simulation (Segment 4)
```

> ⚠️ **Current status:** Default LAN pass rules were removed during setup.
> Must re-add via pfSense web UI (http://172.16.30.1) before VMs can communicate.
> Anti-lockout rule (TCP 80 to pfSense from LAN) is still active.

### Expected Traffic Flows

1. **Normal Operations:**
   - Windows 11 → Wazuh (agent heartbeat every 10s)
   - Switch-1 → Wazuh (system logs)
   - Switch-2 → Wazuh (system logs)
   - pfSense → Wazuh (firewall logs via syslog)

2. **Attack Simulation (Segment 4):**
   - Kali → VLAN 40 (port scan, exploit attempts)
   - Wazuh detects suspicious activity
   - Alerts generated in dashboard

